 Pierre, Achille, Armand, Jean Claude, Jean Jacques, Ketly, Adrien.","French, Walloon, Catalan, English, Jewish (from southern France), West Indian (mainly Haiti), and Mauritian: from (Old) French, Catalan, and Middle English <i>petit</i> ‘small’, hence a nickname for a small man (or an ironic nickname for a big man), or a distinguishing name for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name. Compare   Little  ,   Petee  , and   Petite  .","History: Charles Petit from Anneville-Ambourville in Seine-Maritime, France, married Jeanne Rossignol (Martin and Renée Desjardins) in Quebec City, QC, in 1670. Nicolas Petit <i>dit</i> Lapré/Laprée from Le Gué-d'Alleré in Charente-Maritime, France, married Marie Pouponnel in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1656. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Gobin from Lyon in Rhône married Marguerite Véron in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1692. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Saint-Pierre from Évreux in Eure, France, married Judith Miville in Quebec City, QC, in 1758; see also   St. Pierre  . — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Pettet","meanings":["English: variant of   Pettit  ."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Pettit was born in 1437, in Thanet, Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, Michaell Petit, was 19 and his mother, Julyan Talbot, was 48. He had at least 1 son with Dame Daundelyon. He died on 1 September 1532, in Kent, England, Unit